Basic Structure of a Docker image Tag
-------------------------------------------
Most tags follow this pattern 

>> node:<node_version>-<os>-<variant>
Example : 
>> node:20-bookworm-slim

Node Version number :
------------------------------------
Ex tags: 
25
24
23
22
20

These represent Node.js versions
Ex: 
node:20                 LTS(Very Stable)
node:22                 LTS
node:24                 Future  LTS
node:25                 currnent and newest 

For the production most companies use : 
node:20
node:22

Code names : Some tags include names like
-----------------------------------------
>> iron jod krypton 
These are Node releases codenames 

Ex: 
node:20 → iron
node:22 → jod
node:24 → krypton

So these two are the same : 
node:20
node:iron

Linux distribution :
------------------------------------------
Node images are built on differenct Linux bases

Example: 
Debian Bookworm 
>> node:20-bookworm
Bookworm = Debian 12 ,most stable

Debian bullseye
>> node:20-bullseye
Older Debian version 

Debian Trixie
>> node:20-trixie
Newer Debian testing version 

Alpine Linux
>> node:20-alpine
Very small container Images

Size comparison

| Image                 | Size   |
| --------------------- | ------ |
| node:20               | ~350MB |
| node:20-bookworm-slim | ~80MB  |
| node:20-alpine        | ~40MB  |

Slime Variant:
Ex: 
>> node:20-bookworm-slim
Slim images remove docs ,man pages,extra tools .So the images become smaller

Patch Version:
Ex:
>> 20.20.1
Meaning
major = 20          big version change  [ Breaking changes , Old code may stop working ,API may change ]
minor = 20          new feature added   [ New feature added , backward compatible]
patch = 1           bug fixes / security fixes [ bug fixes , security patches , small  performance imporvement ]

So : 
node:20
actually points to : 
node:20.20.1              

For eample if you write : 
FROM node:20
Docker pulls the latest version inside that major release 
node:20 -> node:20.20.1
Later it may points to node:20.21.3

What production systems use : 
---------------------------------------------
Many companies pin version to avoid surprises
Ex: 
FROM node:20.20.1-slim
This prevents builds from breaking later 

Alpine version :
---------------------------------------------
Example : 
>> node:20-alpine3.23
Meaning :
>> Node 20
>> Alpine Linux 3.23


